ine-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We have heard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in some areas take up of DHP </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is low and therefore there can’t be much of a problem with customers struggling to cope. This is not the case. The low take up is not because of lack of demand, it is lack of access. Many local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ies have failed to establish adequate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> qualifying crite</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ria for DHP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in their area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and as a result claimants are finding it extremely difficult to access the scheme. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, many customers are prioritising their rent payments at the moment whilst the weather is warm. We wait to see what effect winter has o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n arrears rates. When customers are faced with the prospect of paying their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under occupation charge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or staying warm we’re sure we’ll see a further test of the under occupation policy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Voids</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We’re continuing to monitor our void rates to see what impact the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welfare reform changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has on our re-let rates and the demand for different property sizes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst it is difficult to directly attribute void rates statistics to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one single cause we are beginning to build a picture of the effect the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">under-occupation charge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is having on our void rates. Our early findings </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">shows that we are having difficulties letting larger properties (3+ beds) and that re-let times are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increasing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In comparing 2011</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and 2013 re-let times a significant increase can be seen for Scotland (by 54</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.8 days on average) Central (by 30.5 days on average), and the North West (by 22 days on average) in particular for 3 bed properties.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Customers are being made aware of the implications of under-occupation and are not willing (or able) to meet the costs of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> larger properties. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effect is more marked in the north of the country versus the south.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> On some of our estates in the North West and North East the vast majority of our properties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (over 90%)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are 3-bed and as a result there is nowhere within the local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estate that can support the needs of 1-bed and 2-bed families.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These properties, whilst traditionally popular with all customers are increasingly (and reluctantly) being overlooked due to t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he financial implications of the social sector size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Unfor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tunately this is leading to many good quality homes being left void for longer periods as we struggle to find tenants willing to take on family homes. Clearly this was not the Government’s intention when designing the policy but is becoming one of the leas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t desirable perverse consequences of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social sector size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of the changes for claimants </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Behaviour changes</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the South the front line are seeing an increase in refusals for affordable rents properties as only those prospective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> customers claiming Housing Benefit can afford them.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Due to higher rents within the South, the impact of affordable rents has affected our ability to maintain sustainable communities.  Properties which were previously £450 pcm and affordable to self-funder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s are now £700 pcm + and out of their financial reach. Lettings are predominately to those on Housing Benefit which fails to create a mixed community and could deliver greater challenges in income collection with the onset of universal credit. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Due to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lack of demand front line colleagues are having to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> let properties to prospective c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustomers who are not of a high priority banding meaning that in some instances pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-si