 fall either in full or part. Understanding of the government policy and the purpose of Discretionary Housing Payment appears to be varied.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In some instances c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustomers are not contesting the eviction request as they agree they cannot afford to pay the rent. This may be in recognition that support, hotel/B&amp;B accommodation or rapid allocation of new housing may be offered by the Local Authority should the customer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be declared homeless.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The eviction trend for 2013 so far shows that April through August evictions are up by approximately 18% for the same period previous year – in volume there were 60 evictions for arrears in 2012 by August, in 2013 there have been 71 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evictions April through August for arrears. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Additionally, whilst we are finding customers are self-regulating their own housing options due to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social sector size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, we have also changed our allocations policy to ensure we let properties to matc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h household size - further protecting customers from taking on properties that they cannot afford. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Since the implementation of our Allocations Policy in April we have introduced discretionary elements to the policy which, in circumstances where properties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are difficult to let, Home Group will aim to offer the property to prospective tenants who at the point of allocation will be under occupying providing they can evidence they will be able to sustain the tenancy. Where prospective tenants are offered proper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ties outside of the size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the prospective tenants are refusing the properties due to the under occupancy charge further impacting voids and re-let times.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Treatment of housin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g costs within Universal Credit</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Direct payment</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The direct payment of benef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it to customers is one of the main areas of concern we (and the wider sector) have concerning Universal Credit as this is the area we believe our rental income could be most at threat. The direct payment of the housing element of Universal Credit will be a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> huge departure for the majority of our customers and will seriously test the financial management and budgeting skills of some of our customers. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">What is clear from the direct payment pilots</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> currently underway</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is that in all cases, arrears rates went up. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is true despite the significant extra resource each landlord has put in place to manage their arrears due to the changes to direct payments. We, like many others in the sector are keen to learn the lessons of the direct payment pilots when the finding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s are published</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in due course</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Identifying vulnerable customers and switch-back from direct payment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e would urge Government to listen to the expertise of the sector in identifying customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">truggle with direct payments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and allow Registered Pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">viders to put forward credible cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for switch-back to payment to the housing provider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at the outset</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Indications from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Lord Freu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d and the DWP that this will be the case is encouraging , and we would urge Government to work collectively with the sector to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure those that are not ready for the direct payment of Universal Credit are helped through the transition without running up rent arrears.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> It is likely that those customers who are struggling to budget at the moment due to the under occupation charge an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d other welfare changes will be candidates for the housing element of Universal Credit to be paid direct to their landlord. This is likely to mean considerable numbers of cases being brought forward for considera</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion by landlords at the outset.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We recognis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e there is a backstop trigger point to switch-back the housing element of Universal Credit to the Registered Provider following a period of arrears. Whilst this is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">useful (and essential) mechanism</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Home Group believes the early identification of vulnerable customers before arrears occur is far more valuable than an automatic trigger point following arrears.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sanctions under Universal Credit</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We recognise the need for sanctions to be applied to Univers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al Credit claimants where they breach the conditions of their agreement with the DWP, but would urge Government to consider the impact of these sanctions on housing providers. Clearly if Universal Credit payments are stopped or withdrawn the ability of cla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">imants to meet their rent payments will be compromised. Extreme sanctions will in effect transfer the penalty onto housing providers with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">individuals failing to meet their rental payments - with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evictions the ultimate result. We would urge Government to ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rry out a thorough impact assessment of the proposed sanctions to be applied under Universal Credit to ensure penalties applied are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">appropriate and that they are not in effect a direct penalty on housing providers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Supported housing</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Last year the commit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tee recognised</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the additional costs of providing supported housing and called for urgent clarification and finalisation of the future funding arrangements to replace</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘supported exempt accommodation’ rules in Housing Benefit.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcomed Lord Freud’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">announcement at that time that these costs would be paid outside Universal Credit.  However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there has been little clarity about the longer term future, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the interim the current position has been confused by the action of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some local authorities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le there has not been any change to the regulations, our experience is that some local authority housing benefit departments have introduced additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and criteria which are beyond those in the regulations and are demanding inappropriate levels of d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etail from vulnerable claimants.  This is bringing additional cost and uncertainty into the sector as we support clients through the tests and in some cases through appeal processes.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would like to see DWP work with local authority housing benefit depa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rtments to ensure such practices do not take place. We also request swift clarification of how supported exempt accommodation will be funded in the transitional period, and prompt publication of proposals for the longer term funding system.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In considering </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the longer term funding of additional accommodation costs in supported housing, we recognise tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t housing benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will cease</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to exist in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2017 and another solution is required.   We are concerned that government may seek to pass this responsibility to local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> authorities with no national criteria or standards and no certainty of future funding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a national organisation, a completely localised system would require Home Group to meet the requirements of individual local authority funders.  Meeting each of tho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se different systems rather than working to one set of national regulations will lead to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increased administrative costs.  There will be particular impact on services provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> across several local authority areas, and those provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to people who need to mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve out of their area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> but may not have a local connection with the area they move to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, for example victims and survivors of domestic abuse.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusions </span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We will continue to offer support and guidance to our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">customers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as the social sector size criteria and other elements of the Welfare Reform Act come into effect.  However, as a housing association we have a responsibility to all our customers to ensure our rent is collected.  Customers can fall behind in their rent fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r many reasons and we need to treat everyone fairly, including when it comes to rent arrears.  This means that in some cases we may need to take action which includes seeking possession of properties.  Evictions are always the last resort but something we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cannot rule out.  To not do so would significantly impact on our ability to continue to maintain and improve our existing residents’ homes and to provide new homes for future residents.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Our asks of Government</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We welcome the committee’s inquiry into such an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> important</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The pace of change in the welfare reform programme is unprecedented and requires careful monitoring and scrutiny to ensure the changes are implemented fairly. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would urge Government to consider the cumulative effect of the overall welf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are reform agenda as a whole when considering the impact of their welfare reform changes. Individual impact assessments of discrete policy areas mask the wider picture and more work needs to be done to understand the cumulative impacts of all of the change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s (under-occupation charge, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Universal Credit, Council Tax changes, etc)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on individuals and families. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would urge the Government to carefully consider the future of the under occupation policy. The Government’s own impact a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssessment recognises that natio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nally the social housing sector has an oversupply of 3-bed homes and an undersupply of smaller sized accommodation. Families cannot find appropriate sized accommodation as the supply is simply not there. To be penalised as a result is not fair and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the poli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should be looked at again.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ould learn lessons from the roll out of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social sector size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> particularly in relation to information sharing and identifying those affected by new measures. The Government and Local Authorities shou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ld consider standard mechanisms which are consistent across the board relating to information sharing. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be a strengthened commitment to work together with RSL’s to ensure those claimants requiring support are identified early ensuring the nece</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ssa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ry support provisions are put in place.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would urge Government to work with us to ensure that we are notified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">roup c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustomer has made a claim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for Universal Credit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and b) the outcome of the claim – this will allow us to track behaviour a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd offer support plus track and instigate switchback.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also request swift clarification of how supported exempt accommodation will be funded in the transitional period, and prompt publication of proposals for the longer term funding system.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Home Group wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld urge Government to look again at how it proposes to withdraw benefits from individuals when the overall benefit cap is reached. The withdrawal of the housing benefit as the first port of call swiftly increases arrears and significantly increases the ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sk of homelessness.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">26 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">In 2012 Home launched its new way of working </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">with regional contractors in relation to repairs. There have been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> issues with repairs related performance which means comparing 2013 and 2011 is more relevant regarding re-let times.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Universal Credit implementation: meeting the needs of vulnerable c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">laimants - Work and Pensions Committee</span></p></body></html>